mainPoints.content:
Code splitting is your first line of defense against bloated bundle sizes. Instead of loading your entire application upfront, React.lazy() allows you to load components on-demand.

Here's the impact: Our initial bundle size dropped from 2.8MB to 890KB—a 68% reduction—by lazy loading routes and heavy components.

Implementation:
```javascript
const Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import('./Dashboard'));
const Analytics = React.lazy(() => import('./Analytics'));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<LoadingSpinner />}>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
        <Route path="/analytics" element={<Analytics />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

Pro tip: Start with route-level splitting, then identify heavy components within those routes for further optimization.
